727001f-a.text:
Jamaica Ave., at the S.E. corner of 98th Street (formerly Diamond Street), showing in a set of two views the J. B. Napier farmhouse from 1860 to 1891. In view No. 2 is seen the Jamaica Ave. B.M.T. elevated line extending over Jamaica Ave. behind the house.

April 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

725750f-a.text:
98th Street, adjoining the northwest corner of Jamaica Avenue, showing the J. B. Napier house. It was built by John B. Napier, who settled in Woodhaven in 1844 and died in 1890. The Napier farmland comprised 7.7 acres (1909), extending north from Jamaica avenue, along what is now 98th Street, to Park Lane South, the southern boundary of Forest Park. The eastern limit was
the Long Island Railroad bed.
Eugene L. Arubruster Collection  April, 1923

725751f-a.text:
98th Street (formerly Diamond Street), west side, north of Jamaica Ave., showing in a set of two views the John B. Napier farmhouse of 1860. J. Napier was the owner in 1891. The first Napier settled here in 1844 and died in 1890. "At a meeting of the inhabitants of Woodville, held in August 1853, Dominicus; Vandeveer being chairman, the name was changed to 'Woodhaven.'
August 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
